I was at one end of a large flock of snow geese that was fairly calm at this time so  individual calls stand out. A Black-capped Chickadee came by too.

At 1:59pm, 500 Snow Geese sitting on Blackwater River erupted into flight -- predator avoidance behavior -- wheeled about together and landed in about the same place. I did not see or hear the perceived threat to the SNGO, but 10 minutes before there was a Bald Eagle (and it was recorded and included in this checklist).

mediaNotes: low flight over field

The exact moment the group was flushed by a golfer/maintenance person.  You can hear the wingbeats of the flock in the beginning.  They flew east towards Makamah, but later in the recording (00:40) you can hear them come back to the driving range giving a lot of cool vocalizations. Constant plane/car noise.
Recordist's Notes: ID certainty 100%.

NOTES: WHOLE FLOCK IN AIR, THEN SETTLE DOWN. THE NOISE SEEMED TO CONNECTED WITH EXCITEMENT AND GRADUALLY DIED DOWN AS THE BIRDS RESUMED FEEDING WITHOUT INTERRUPTION. THEN THE FLOCK, OR A LARGE PART OF IT, TAKES TO THE AIR AND SETTLES DOWN AGAIN. THEN  Sex: 10000 UNKNOWN BIRDS BECOME VERY QUIET. FLOCK GOES UP, SETTLES DOWN, AND BECOMES VERY QUIET SEVERAL TIMES. SOME GOOD INDIVIDUALS TOWARDS END OF CUT. FLOCK OF 5000-10000 BLUE PHASE GEESE. Other Behaviors: Arrive, Depart.

Calls from a single individual with Canada flock on the pond. Calling sporadically, initially spontaneously but most often in later cuts in response to my movements. Lots of Canada Goose noise in the background.
Equipment Notes: Recorded with a Telinga Pro, model unknown.
